<subSubSection id="8081656D9807700D1BB0F920FD9DAC87" pageId="16" pageNumber="227" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="C82436E69807700D1BB0F920FE46AC3B" blockId="16.[151,445,1772,1798]" box="[151,445,1772,1798]" pageId="16" pageNumber="227">
<heading id="936C818A9807700D1BB0F920FE46AC3B" bold="true" box="[151,445,1772,1798]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="16" pageNumber="227" reason="1">
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49807700D1BB0F920FE46AC3B" bold="true" box="[151,445,1772,1798]" pageId="16" pageNumber="227">
Family 
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659807700D1BD0F920FE46AC3B" box="[247,445,1772,1798]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Carcharhinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Carcharhinidae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C82436E69807700D1BB0F8F8FD9DAC87" blockId="16.[151,1436,1844,2015]" pageId="16" pageNumber="227">
Species from the family 
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659807700D1A99F8F8FD92AC73" box="[446,617,1844,1870]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Carcharhinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Carcharhinidae</taxonomicName>
are the most commonly landed shark in 
<collectingCountry id="B08C76769807700D1F7EF8F8FB24AC73" box="[1113,1247,1844,1870]" name="Bangladesh" pageId="16" pageNumber="227">Bangladesh</collectingCountry>
, with 
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659807700D1E0BF8F8FEF7AC4F" authorityName="Muller &amp; Henle" authorityYear="1838" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Carcharhinidae" genus="Scoliodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="laticaudus">
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49807700D1E0BF8F8FEF7AC4F" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="227">Scoliodon laticaudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the most frequently caught. Smaller carcharhinids tend to be piled together, and are difficult to sample individually. The presence of 
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659807700D1AD3F8B0FD14ACAB" authorityName="Muller &amp; Henle" authorityYear="1839" box="[500,751,1916,1942]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Carcharhinidae" genus="Loxodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrorhinus">
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49807700D1AD3F8B0FD14ACAB" box="[500,751,1916,1942]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="227">Loxodon macrorhinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was confirmed, warranting further investigation, including specimen collection and genetic analysis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8081656D9807700C1BE0F809FCAEA860" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="228" pageId="16" pageNumber="227" type="description">
<paragraph id="C82436E69807700C1BE0F809FB10AA7C" blockId="16.[151,1436,1844,2015]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1437,151,861]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="228" pageId="16" pageNumber="227">
Most of the reported species in this study inhabit depths between 
<quantity id="0F639B039807700D188DF809FBE2ACE2" box="[938,1049,1989,2015]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="227" unit="m" value="70.0" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="40.0">40-100 m</quantity>
, while a few species are known to occur at depths over 
<quantity id="0F639B039806700C1AA4FF5BFE31AB8C" box="[387,458,151,177]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" unit="m" value="100.0">100 m</quantity>
(e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659806700C192CFF5BFD61AB8C" box="[523,666,151,177]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Mobula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49806700C192CFF5BFD99AB8C" box="[523,610,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">Mobula</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659806700C1981FF5BFC80AB8D" baseAuthorityName="Norman" baseAuthorityYear="1939" box="[678,891,151,177]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Triakidae" genus="Iago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omanensis">
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49806700C1981FF5BFD22AB8D" box="[678,729,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">Iago</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49806700C1822FF5BFC80AB8D" box="[773,891,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">omanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Many of the species, particularly the stingrays (
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659806700C1BB8FF77FEE4ABEB" box="[159,287,187,214]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Dasyatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Dasyatidae</taxonomicName>
) mostly occur in coastal and inner shelf waters (mostly &lt;
<quantity id="0F639B039806700C1881FF77FC1DABE8" box="[934,998,187,213]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" unit="m" value="100.0">100m</quantity>
depth), particularly around mangroves (
<bibRefCitation id="AC0A4B179806700C1BB8FF13FEA4ABC7" author="Last, P. &amp; Naylor, G. &amp; Seret, B. &amp; White, W. &amp; de Carvalho, M. &amp; Stehmann, M." box="[159,351,223,250]" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" refId="ref7175" refString="Last, P., Naylor, G., Seret, B., White, W., de Carvalho, M. &amp; Stehmann, M. (2016 a) Rays of the World. CSIRO publishing, Melbourne, ix + 790 pp." type="book" year="2016">
Last 
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49806700C1BF0FF13FEF4ABC4" box="[215,271,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">et al.</emphasis>
2016a
</bibRefCitation>
). Almost all shallow water coastal and marine areas are exploited by artisanal fishing. The lack of deep-water species is expected as artisanal fishing is limited to waters shallower than 
<specimenCount id="DE9DFD6F9806700C1F6AFECFFB61AA20" box="[1101,1178,259,285]" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" type="generic">
<quantity id="0F639B039806700C1F6AFECFFB6DAA20" box="[1101,1174,259,285]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" unit="m" value="200.0">200 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
Future sampling of the catch from mid and deep-water industrial vessels may result in further new records for the country.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C82436E69806700C1BE0FE87FF13A9CC" blockId="17.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">
Of the possible new records, one species, 
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49806700C198CFE87FC65AA58" box="[683,926,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659806700C198CFE87FC61AA58" authorityName="Manjaji-Matsumoto &amp; Last" authorityYear="2016" box="[683,922,331,357]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Maculabatis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arabica">Maculabatis arabica</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
is designated as Critically Endangered, four as Endangered (
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49806700C1A71FEA3FA68AAB4" box="[342,1427,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659806700C1A71FEA3FDDAAAB4" box="[342,545,367,393]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Mobula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="thurstoni">Mobula thurstoni</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659806700C1915FEA3FCDCAAB4" baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[562,807,367,393]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Urogymnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="polylepis">Urogymnus polylepis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659806700C181FFEA3FBCBAAB5" baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[824,1072,367,393]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Maculabatis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrura">Maculabatis macrura</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659806700C1F54FEA3FA68AAB4" authorityName="Last, Manjaji &amp; Yearsley" authorityYear="2005" box="[1139,1427,367,393]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Pastinachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="solocirostris">Pastinachus solocirostris</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
) and three as Vulnerable by the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species (
<tableCitation id="8519035D9806700C18E4FE5FFBE2AA90" box="[963,1049,403,429]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,235,521,546]" captionText="TABLE 1. List of species reported in this paper from the southeast coastal region of Bangladesh with habitat type and global distribution (Last et al., 2016a, Froese and Pauly 2000), Global IUCN Red List of Threatened status (EN: Endangered; NT: Near Threatened; VU: Vulnerable; DD: Data Deficient; LC: Least Concern; NE: Not evaluated), assessment dates, CITES, and CMS status are given with comments on their identifications." pageId="17" pageNumber="228">Table 1</tableCitation>
), though many have not yet been evaluated. One species (
<emphasis id="FAEFEAF49806700C1A8EFE7BFDC5AAEC" box="[425,574,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">
<taxonomicName id="0F9B4D659806700C1A8EFE7BFDCEAAEC" box="[425,565,439,465]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Mobula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="thurstoni">M. thurstoni</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
is listed by the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) and The Convention on Migratory Species (CMS). 
<collectingCountry id="B08C76769806700C1F19FE17FB3AAAC8" box="[1086,1217,475,501]" name="Bangladesh" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">Bangladesh</collectingCountry>
protects 29 species of elasmobranchs under the Wildlife (Conservation and Security) Act, 2012. Recently, 
<collectingCountry id="B08C76769806700C1F57FE33FB08A924" box="[1136,1267,511,537]" name="Bangladesh" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">Bangladesh</collectingCountry>
has responded to global concern for elasmobranch populations, by planning the amendment of this Act for better protection of the most threatened species (J. Kabir, Director, Sheikh Kamal Wildlife Centre, 
<collectingCountry id="B08C76769806700C18DFFD8BFB80A95C" box="[1016,1147,583,609]" name="Bangladesh" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">Bangladesh</collectingCountry>
Forest Department, pers. comm. 28 Feb, 2020). Moreover, developing non-detrimental findings (NDFs) (
<bibRefCitation id="AC0A4B179806700C1F00FDA7FB5FA9B8" author="Rose, M." box="[1063,1188,619,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="228" pagination="1 - 98" refId="ref7781" refString="Rose, M. (2014) Non-detriment Findings in CITES (NDFs). Austrian Federal Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry, Environment and Water Management, 1 (2), 1 - 98." type="journal article" year="2014">Rose 2014</bibRefCitation>
) is also a top priority for the country in 2020. However, such initiatives need to be underpinned by solid scientific understanding, such as provided in this study, as a lack of accurate taxonomic and species-specific information impedes conservation efforts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C82436E69806700C1BE0FD37FCAEA860" blockId="17.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="17" pageNumber="228">In the absence of a regional identification guide and reliable species checklist, field-level research work is impeded. The current study and our ongoing work (Haque et al. in review) will lead to such a guide in the future, contributing to better taxonomic resolution for several species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
